```

saves you from writing a million null checks.

generics let you write code that works with any type without losing type safety.

```ts
// without generics — loses type info
function first(arr: any[]): any {
  return arr[0];
}

// with generics — preserves the type
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T {
  return arr[0];
}

first([1, 2, 3]);       // TypeScript knows this returns number
first(['a', 'b', 'c']); // TypeScript knows this returns string
```

the `<T>` is a placeholder. it gets replaced with the actual type when you use the function. think of it as a variable for types.

instead of adding event listeners to every child element, you add one listener to the parent and let events bubble up.

```js
// bad — 100 buttons = 100 listeners
document.querySelectorAll('.btn').forEach(btn => {
  btn.addEventListener('click', handler);
});

// good — 1 listener catches all
document.getElementById('toolbar').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  if (e.target.matches('.btn')) handler(e);
});
```

way more efficient and works for dynamically added elements too.

```js
function debounce(fn, delay = 300) {
  let timer;
  return (...args) => {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), delay);
  };
}

// usage — only fires 300ms after user stops typing
const search = debounce((query) => {
  fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`);
}, 300);

input.addEventListener('input', (e) => search(e.target.value));
```

it waits until the user stops doing the thing before actually running. essential for search inputs and window resize handlers.

