a webhook is a URL that gets called automatically when something happens. like a notification system between servers.

instead of you constantly asking "did anything change?" (polling), the other service calls YOUR endpoint when something happens (push).

```js
// your server listens for webhook events
app.post('/webhook/stripe', (req, res) => {
  const event = req.body;
  if (event.type === 'payment_intent.succeeded') {
    // payment went through!
    fulfillOrder(event.data);
  }
  res.sendStatus(200);
});
```

Stripe, GitHub, Slack — they all use webhooks. "when X happens, hit this URL and tell me."

JSON Web Token — a compact way to handle authentication without sessions.

```
header.payload.signature
eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoxfQ.signature_here
```

flow:
1. user logs in with email/password
2. server creates a JWT with user info inside
3. client stores it (localStorage or cookie)
4. client sends it with every request in the Authorization header
5. server verifies the signature — no database lookup needed

```js
// server creates token
const token = jwt.sign({ userId: 1 }, SECRET_KEY, { expiresIn: '24h' });

// client sends it
fetch('/api/data', {
  headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` }
});
```

stateless auth — the server doesn't need to store sessions. just verify the signature.

PUT replaces the entire resource. PATCH updates only specific fields.

```
PUT /api/users/1
{ "name": "Jumar", "age": 24, "email": "j@bleumr.com" }
// replaces the WHOLE user object

PATCH /api/users/1
{ "age": 24 }
// only updates age, everything else stays the same
```

use PATCH when you only want to change one or two fields. use PUT when you're sending the complete updated object. in practice, most APIs use PATCH for updates.

browser storage that persists even after you close the tab.

```js
// save data
localStorage.setItem('theme', 'dark');
localStorage.setItem('user', JSON.stringify({ name: 'Jumar' }));

// read data
const theme = localStorage.getItem('theme'); // 'dark'
const user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('user'));

// remove
localStorage.removeItem('theme');
localStorage.clear(); // nuke everything
```

limits:
- ~5MB per domain
- strings only (JSON.stringify objects)
- synchronous (blocks the main thread)
- no expiration — stays forever unless you clear it

good for: user preferences, theme settings, small cached data. NOT for sensitive data — it's accessible to any JS on the page.
